THEORY DISCOVERY NOTE — VERTICAL PRIMITIVE DISCOVERY
------------------------------------------------------------

Author: Kok Pian Gew
Date: 2026
Status: Conceptual research note

Summary
------------------------------------------------------------

This note records a methodological observation encountered during
the development of the Trust Framework and the Continuation Framework.

The observation concerns how new theoretical primitives may be
discovered using an existing theoretical structure.

Rather than beginning with primitives directly, theory development
often begins with observable systems or coordination mechanisms.
As the theory evolves, unresolved dependencies within the structure
can reveal deeper explanatory layers.

This process can be described as "vertical theory discovery".

In vertical discovery, an existing framework acts as a structural
probe that exposes deeper primitive conditions required for the
framework to function.

Example from this research
------------------------------------------------------------

Trust Framework
(4 Pillars: Interpersonal, Identity, Structural, Capacity)

↓ investigation of system stability

Requirement for persistent cooperation

↓ deeper condition identified

Continuation

In this case, continuation was identified as a deeper primitive
condition underlying trust formation and cooperation systems.

Thus the relationship becomes:

Continuation
↓
Coexistence systems
↓
Coordination mechanisms
↓
Trust formation
↓
Institutional structures

Implication
------------------------------------------------------------

A well-structured framework can therefore function as a
methodological tool for discovering deeper primitives.

Internal tensions or unanswered questions within a theory
can guide researchers toward more fundamental explanatory
conditions.

This observation suggests a possible methodology for
discovering new theoretical primitives through structured
framework exploration.

Status
------------------------------------------------------------

This document records an early-stage methodological insight.
Further validation would require examination across additional
historical or scientific examples.

