THEORY DISCOVERY — COMPARATIVE CONTEXT
------------------------------------------------------------

Purpose
------------------------------------------------------------

The process described in this work — identifying a deeper
primitive by examining the internal requirements of an
existing conceptual framework — can be understood within
a broader landscape of theory discovery methods.

This section briefly compares the approach used in this
project with several well-known traditions in scientific
and philosophical theory development.


------------------------------------------------------------
1. First-Principle Reduction
------------------------------------------------------------

Method

Many foundational theories are constructed by identifying
irreducible primitives from which all other concepts can
be derived.

Examples

• Newtonian mechanics (force, mass, motion)
• Thermodynamics (energy, entropy)
• Information theory (information, entropy)

Comparison

The continuation framework follows a similar pattern.

Rather than treating trust as primitive, the investigation
revealed that trust itself depends on a deeper condition:

continuation of interaction across time.

Thus continuation functions as a lower-level primitive
from which trust mechanisms emerge.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. Systems Theory
------------------------------------------------------------

Method

Systems theory examines how complex structures maintain
stability through interaction among components.

Examples

• General Systems Theory (Ludwig von Bertalanffy)
• Cybernetics (Norbert Wiener)
• Complex adaptive systems

Comparison

Systems theory focuses on stability and feedback within
existing systems.

The continuation framework instead asks a more fundamental
question:

What condition must exist for coordinated systems to persist
at all?

The answer proposed here is continuation across time.


------------------------------------------------------------
3. Evolutionary Explanation
------------------------------------------------------------

Method

Evolutionary frameworks explain the emergence of cooperation
through survival advantages.

Examples

• Evolutionary game theory
• Kin selection
• Reciprocal altruism

Comparison

Evolutionary models typically explain why cooperation can
emerge.

The continuation framework instead examines the structural
conditions that make repeated cooperation meaningful.

Trust emerges when agents expect the relationship to continue.


------------------------------------------------------------
4. Institutional Economics
------------------------------------------------------------

Method

Institutional theory studies how rules and norms enable
coordination among individuals.

Examples

• Elinor Ostrom — governance of common resources
• Douglass North — institutions and economic performance

Comparison

Institutional theories examine how rules stabilize cooperation.

The continuation framework suggests that these rules are
secondary coordination mechanisms.

Their underlying purpose is to sustain continuation of
cooperative interaction.


------------------------------------------------------------
5. Information Processing Perspective
------------------------------------------------------------

Method

Many modern frameworks interpret social and economic systems
as information processing structures.

Examples

• Information theory
• Computational social science
• Signal processing models of markets

Comparison

The Trust Framework interprets contribution events as signals
transmitted through coordination systems.

However signal interpretation itself requires an underlying
temporal structure.

Continuation provides the temporal horizon that gives
meaning to these signals.


------------------------------------------------------------
6. Methodological Distinction
------------------------------------------------------------

The discovery process used in this project differs slightly
from traditional first-principle construction.

Rather than beginning directly from primitives, the process
began with a structured framework (Trust Framework).

By examining the internal dependencies of that framework,
a deeper primitive became visible.

This approach may be described as:

vertical primitive discovery.

Existing frameworks can therefore function as exploratory
structures that reveal deeper explanatory conditions.


